\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240

\f1 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
LifeTree is a combination of a mobile application and a physical artefact that helps people to balance their different and important life aspects. The LifeTree application gathers and analyses data from the user\'92s smartphone and social networks among others, based on the user\'92s choices. Then it gives feedback in an aesthetic visualization in form of a tree where each branch has a different meaning and symbolizes different life aspects. The feedback that will be given to the users shows how well they balance their life and has the appearance of a tree. Also, proper advices will be given on how to improve their life balance in an easily acceptable way. The user will also see the changes in a physical artefact, with the same shape of the tree that is connected to the mobile application and could be used as a decoration in one\'92s home. The physical artifact will change according to the application and show different colors and branches according to the current state of the user\'92s life balance. \
\
Process:\
1. Research of Quantified Self\
In this course we got our subject domain: quantified self. Mind map was used to understand this subject, and what potential design direction could we lead to. After some literature research and brainstorming, three main categories under quantified self were identified. Firstly, the physiological data including hearing rate, calories burnt, weight, etc. These data were mostly numeric numbers that told one\'92s health, or performance of athletes. The second category included one\'92s emotion data such as level of happiness, sadness and stressfulness. This category of data were mainly self ratings and descriptions that could help assess patients, help prisoners keep mentally health, or help to play the right music according to one\'92s mood. The third category of data were a new category we called \'91personal data\'92 which has wide range of variety such as the dress code of everyday dress, the number of people met everyday, personal log of self-awareness and self-improvement, and one\'92s physical path.\
